The Machine Learning model is designed to predict the likelihood of heart disease by analyzing multiple cardiovascular health parameters collected from patient data. It is trained on structured medical datasets containing features such as age, gender, chest pain type, resting blood pressure, cholesterol levels, fasting blood sugar, ECG results, maximum heart rate, exercise-induced angina, ST depression, and other clinical indicators.

The model performs data preprocessing, feature analysis, normalization, and pattern recognition to identify relationships between medical attributes and heart disease outcomes. Various supervised learning algorithms can be used, including Logistic Regression, Random Forest, Decision Trees, Support Vector Machines, or Gradient Boosting, to improve prediction accuracy and reliability.

After training, the model evaluates unseen patient data and generates real-time predictions indicating the probability of cardiovascular disease risk. The system is optimized for fast inference, accurate classification, and scalability, making it suitable for healthcare analytics, early diagnosis assistance, and intelligent medical decision-support applications.
